Once more then these last four lines, applied as a touchstone to the interpretation of the poem as a whole, put us instantly on our guard, and save us from extravagances. They seem to bring us back to Virgil‚ to Italy, and to common sense3 and no one has a right to deal with the Eclogue who will not give them their due place in it. But they present more than one serious difficulty, and I must now proceed to examine them in detail.
